         <t:listPerson>
            <t:person sex="1">
               <t:persName xml:id="n1" xml:lang="am">ምርጫ፡ ወርቄ፡
               </t:persName>
               <t:persName corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Mǝrč̣ā Warqe</t:persName>
              <t:persName xml:lang="en" corresp="#n1">M. Warkee</t:persName>
               <t:persName><t:roleName type="title">liqa makʷās</t:roleName></t:persName>
               <t:persName><t:roleName type="title">lǝǧ</t:roleName></t:persName>
               <t:occupation type="political"/>
               <t:birth when="1825"/>
               <t:floruit>He was one of the first foreign-educated Ethiopians who acted as a diplomat, secretary and interpreter.
Mǝrč̣ā Warqe received his education at the British missionary school of John Wilson in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1956Bombay">Bombay</t:placeName>.
In <t:date>1849</t:date> he left India and founded a school in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1264Adwa">ʿĀdwā</t:placeName> together with his
brother <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4398GabruWa"> Gäbru Wärqe </t:persName>. Later, Mǝrč̣ā Warqe became a follower of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9430Tewodros">Tewodros II</t:persName>.
He played a crucial political role during the British military compaign led by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7484Napier">Robert Cornelis Napier</t:persName>.
Mǝrč̣ā Warqe established contact between <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7484Napier">Robert Cornelis Napier</t:persName> and <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10378Yohanne">ʾaṣe Yoḥannǝs IV</t:persName>,
thus securing support for <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10378Yohanne">ʾaṣe Yoḥannǝs IV</t:persName> after the downfall of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9430Tewodros">Tewodros II</t:persName>.
In <t:date>1875</t:date> Mǝrč̣ā Warqe was an envoy of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10378Yohanne">ʾaṣe Yoḥannǝs IV</t:persName> in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2085Cairo">Cairo</t:placeName>.
In <t:date>1884</t:date> he acted as a secretary of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10378Yohanne">ʾaṣe Yoḥannǝs IV</t:persName>, and in <t:date>1896</t:date> he served as
an interpreter for <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6668Mangasa">Mangašā Yoḥannǝs</t:persName>.
               </t:floruit>
               <t:death notBefore="1896"/>
            </t:person>
            
